  "content": [
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "level": 1,
      "text": "JavaScript Bitwise Operations"
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "level": 2,
      "text": "JavaScript Bitwise Operators"
    },
    {
      "type": "table",
      "data": [
        [
          "Operator",
          "Name",
          "Description"
        ],
        [
          "&",
          "AND",
          "Sets each bit to 1 if both bits are 1"
        ],
        [
          "|",
          "OR",
          "Sets each bit to 1 if one of two bits is 1"
        ],
        [
          "^",
          "XOR",
          "Sets each bit to 1 if only one of two bits is 1"
        ],
        [
          "~",
          "NOT",
          "Inverts all the bits"
        ],
        [
          "<<",
          "Zero fill left shift",
          "Shifts left by pushing zeros in from the right and let the leftmost bits fall off"
        ],
        [
          ">>",
          "Signed right shift",
          "Shifts right by pushing copies of the leftmost bit in from the left, and let the rightmost bits \nfall off"
        ],
        [
          ">>>",
          "Zero fill right shift",
          "Shifts right by pushing zeros in from the left, and let the rightmost bits fall off"
        ]
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "level": 2,
      "text": "Examples"
    },
    {
      "type": "other",
      "text": "Operation\nResult\nSame as\nResult\n\n\n5 & 1\n1\n0101 & 0001\n 0001\n\n\n5 | 1\n5\n0101 | 0001\n 0101\n\n\n~ 5\n10\n ~0101\n 1010\n\n\n5 << 1\n10\n0101 << 1\n 1010\n\n\n5 ^ 1\n4\n0101 ^ 0001\n 0100\n\n\n5 >> 1\n2\n0101 >> 1\n 0010\n\n\n5 >>> 1\n2\n0101 >>> 1\n 0010"
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "level": 2,
      "text": "JavaScript Uses 32 bits Bitwise Operands"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "JavaScript stores numbers as 64 bits floating point numbers, but all bitwise \noperations are performed on 32 bits binary numbers."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Before a bitwise operation is performed, JavaScript converts numbers to 32 bits \nsigned integers."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "After the bitwise operation is performed, the result is converted back to 64 bits JavaScript \nnumbers."
    },
    {
      "type": "other",
      "text": "The examples above uses 4 bits unsigned binary numbers. Because of this ~ 5 returns 10.\nSince JavaScript uses 32 bits signed integers, it will not return 10. It will return -6.\n00000000000000000000000000000101 (5)\n11111111111111111111111111111010 (~5 = -6)\nA signed integer uses the leftmost bit as the minus sign."
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "level": 2,
      "text": "JavaScript Bitwise AND"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "When a bitwise AND is performed on a pair of bits, it returns 1 if both bits are 1."
    },
    {
      "type": "other",
      "text": "One bit example:\n\n  OperationResult\n  0 & 00\n  0 & 10\n  1 & 00\n  1 & 11\n\n\n\n4 bits example:\n\n  OperationResult\n  1111 & 00000000\n  1111 & 00010001\n  1111 & 00100010\n  1111 & 01000100"
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "level": 2,
      "text": "JavaScript Bitwise OR"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "When a bitwise OR is performed on a pair of bits, it returns 1 if one of the bits is 1:"
    },
    {
      "type": "other",
      "text": "One bit example:\n\n  OperationResult\n  0 | 00\n  0 | 11 \n  1 | 01\n  1 | 11\n\n\n\n4 bits example:\n\n  OperationResult\n  1111 | 00001111\n  1111 | 00011111\n  1111 | 00101111\n  1111 | 01001111"
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "level": 2,
      "text": "JavaScript Bitwise XOR"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "When a bitwise XOR is performed on a pair of bits, it returns 1 if the bits are different:"
    },
    {
      "type": "other",
      "text": "One bit example:\n\n  OperationResult\n  0 ^ 00\n  0 ^ 11 \n  1 ^ 01\n  1 ^ 10 \n\n\n\n4 bits example:\n\n  OperationResult\n  1111 ^ 00001111\n  1111 ^ 00011110\n  1111 ^ 00101101\n  1111 ^ 01001011"
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "level": 2,
      "text": "JavaScript Bitwise AND (&)"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Bitwise AND returns 1 only if both bits are 1:"
    },
    {
      "type": "table",
      "data": [
        [
          "Decimal",
          "Binary"
        ],
        [
          "5",
          "00000000000000000000000000000101"
        ],
        [
          "1",
          "00000000000000000000000000000001"
        ],
        [
          "5 & 1",
          "00000000000000000000000000000001 (1)"
        ]
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "example",
      "description": "",
      "codes": [
        {
          "language": "unknown",
          "code": "let x = 5 & 1;"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "level": 2,
      "text": "JavaScript Bitwise OR (|)"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Bitwise OR returns 1 if one of the bits is 1:"
    },
    {
      "type": "table",
      "data": [
        [
          "Decimal",
          "Binary"
        ],
        [
          "5",
          "00000000000000000000000000000101"
        ],
        [
          "1",
          "00000000000000000000000000000001"
        ],
        [
          "5 | 1",
          "00000000000000000000000000000101 (5)"
        ]
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "example",
      "description": "",
      "codes": [
        {
          "language": "unknown",
          "code": "let x = 5 | 1;"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "level": 2,
      "text": "JavaScript Bitwise XOR (^)"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Bitwise XOR returns 1 if the bits are different:"
    },
    {
      "type": "table",
      "data": [
        [
          "Decimal",
          "Binary"
        ],
        [
          "5",
          "00000000000000000000000000000101"
        ],
        [
          "1",
          "00000000000000000000000000000001"
        ],
        [
          "5 ^ 1",
          "00000000000000000000000000000100 (4)"
        ]
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "example",
      "description": "",
      "codes": [
        {
          "language": "unknown",
          "code": "let x = 5 ^ 1;"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "level": 2,
      "text": "JavaScript Bitwise NOT (~)"
    },
    {
      "type": "table",
      "data": [
        [
          "Decimal",
          "Binary"
        ],
        [
          "5",
          "00000000000000000000000000000101"
        ],
        [
          "~5",
          "11111111111111111111111111111010 (-6)"
        ]
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "example",
      "description": "",
      "codes": [
        {
          "language": "unknown",
          "code": "let x = ~5;"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "level": 2,
      "text": "JavaScript (Zero Fill) Bitwise Left Shift (<<)"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "This is a zero fill left shift. One or more zero bits are pushed in from the right,\nand the leftmost bits fall off:"
    },
    {
      "type": "table",
      "data": [
        [
          "Decimal",
          "Binary"
        ],
        [
          "5",
          "00000000000000000000000000000101"
        ],
        [
          "5 << 1",
          "00000000000000000000000000001010 (10)"
        ]
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "example",
      "description": "",
      "codes": [
        {
          "language": "unknown",
          "code": "let x = 5 << 1;"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "level": 2,
      "text": "JavaScript (Sign Preserving) Bitwise Right Shift (>>)"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "This is a sign preserving right shift. Copies of the leftmost bit are pushed \nin from the left, and the rightmost bits fall off:"
    },
    {
      "type": "table",
      "data": [
        [
          "Decimal",
          "Binary"
        ],
        [
          "-5",
          "11111111111111111111111111111011"
        ],
        [
          "-5 >> 1",
          "11111111111111111111111111111101 (-3)"
        ]
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "example",
      "description": "",
      "codes": [
        {
          "language": "unknown",
          "code": "let x = -5 >> 1;"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "level": 2,
      "text": "JavaScript (Zero Fill) Right Shift (>>>)"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "This is a zero fill right shift. One or more zero bits are pushed in from the left,\nand the rightmost bits fall off:"
    },
    {
      "type": "table",
      "data": [
        [
          "Decimal",
          "Binary"
        ],
        [
          "5",
          "00000000000000000000000000000101"
        ],
        [
          "5 >>> 1",
          "00000000000000000000000000000010 (2)"
        ]
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "example",
      "description": "",
      "codes": [
        {
          "language": "unknown",
          "code": "let x = 5 >>> 1;"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "level": 2,
      "text": "Binary Numbers"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Binary numbers with only one bit set are easy to understand:"
    },
    {
      "type": "table",
      "data": [
        [
          "Binary Representation",
          "Decimal value"
        ],
        [
          "00000000000000000000000000000001",
          "1"
        ],
        [
          "00000000000000000000000000000010",
          "2"
        ],
        [
          "00000000000000000000000000000100",
          "4"
        ],
        [
          "00000000000000000000000000001000",
          "8"
        ],
        [
          "00000000000000000000000000010000",
          "16"
        ],
        [
          "00000000000000000000000000100000",
          "32"
        ],
        [
          "00000000000000000000000001000000",
          "64"
        ]
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Setting a few more bits reveals the binary pattern:"
    },
    {
      "type": "table",
      "data": [
        [
          "Binary Representation",
          "Decimal value"
        ],
        [
          "00000000000000000000000000000101",
          "5 (4 + 1)"
        ],
        [
          "00000000000000000000000000001101",
          "13 (8 + 4 + 1)"
        ],
        [
          "00000000000000000000000000101101",
          "45 (32 + 8 + 4 + 1)"
        ]
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "JavaScript binary numbers are stored in two's complement format."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "This means that a negative number is the bitwise NOT of the number plus 1:"
    },
    {
      "type": "table",
      "data": [
        [
          "Binary Representation",
          "Decimal value"
        ],
        [
          "00000000000000000000000000000101",
          "5"
        ],
        [
          "11111111111111111111111111111011",
          "-5"
        ],
        [
          "00000000000000000000000000000110",
          "6"
        ],
        [
          "11111111111111111111111111111010",
          "-6"
        ],
        [
          "00000000000000000000000000101000",
          "40"
        ],
        [
          "11111111111111111111111111011000",
          "-40"
        ]
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "other",
      "text": "Joke:\nThere are only 10 types of people in the world: those who understand binary and those who don't."
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "level": 2,
      "text": "Converting Decimal to Binary"
    },
    {
      "type": "example",
      "description": "",
      "codes": [
        {
          "language": "unknown",
          "code": "function dec2bin(dec){\n  return (dec >>> 0).toString(2);\n}"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "level": 2,
      "text": "Converting Binary to Decimal"
    },
    {
      "type": "example",
      "description": "",
      "codes": [
        {
          "language": "unknown",
          "code": "function bin2dec(bin){\n    return parseInt(bin, 2).toString(10);\n}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
}